star  aThis book documents and assesses the core of New Labour's approach to the revitalisation of cities, that is, the revival of citizenship, democratic renewal, and the participation of communities to spear head urban change. In doing so, the book explores the meaning, and relevance, of 'community' as a focus for urban renaissance. It interrogates the conceptual and ideological content of New Labour's conceptions of community and, through the use of case studies, evaluates how far, and with what effects, such conceptions are shaping contemporary urban policy and practice. The book is an important text for students and researchers in geography, urban studies, planning, sociology, and related disciplines. It will also be of interest to officers working in local and central government, voluntary organisations, community groups, and those with a stake in seeking to enhance democracy and community involvement in urban policy and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzGreat Britain. 0aUrban policyzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCochrane, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHastings, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImrie, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImrie, Rob, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKearns, Ade, econtributor.4ctb4https: